<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12145f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12145f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12145f"> 145(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Maol (bald) is like / Caplait</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&laquo;Cependant, les cris de douleur qu&apos;arrach&egrave;rent &agrave; leurs compagnes la mort des jeunes fulles, firent accourir l&apos;un des deux mages auxquels l&apos;&eacute;ducation d&apos;Ethnae et de Fedelm avait &eacute;t&eacute; confi&eacute;e par le roi. Ce mage s&apos;appelait caplait; il entendit l&apos;enseignement de P, il crut, et on lui rasa la t&ecirc;te. L&apos;autre mage arriva &agrave; son tour; son nom &eacute;tait Ma&euml;l.Il r&eacute;sista d&apos;abord &agrave; la parole de P, puis enfin de convertit et il eut la t&ecirc;te ras&eacute;e, d&apos;o&ugrave; le proverbe: &laquo;Ma&euml;l est comme Caplait.&raquo; <br><font color="green">[82-3: Now the death of these young maidens drew forth such lamentations from their companions that one of the two Druids to whom their father had entrusted the education of Ethne and Fieldelm, hastened to the spot. The name of this Druid was Caplait; he listened to the teaching of Patrick, was converted, and received the tonsure. The other priest named Ma&euml;l followed in his turn; he at first resisted, but at length believed Patrick&apos;s teaching and also received the tonsure. Hence the proverb, &ldquo;<mark>Ma&euml;l est comme Caplait</mark>.&rdquo;]</font> <small> Riguet, Abb&eacute; <a name="RTSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RTSP"><cite title="source">Saint Patrice</cite></a> (1911) 98-9</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
